{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UnB6oUWyoBGyx7EUgMrAq6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The admission webhook is blocking the configuration-snippet annotation because it's considered \"risky.\" This is because newer versions of ingress-nginx restrict configuration-snippet annotations by default.\n\nHowever, in the ConfigMap I see `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` is already set. But the admission webhook might have a stricter check. Let me check if there's a way to bypass this.\n\nActually, looking at newer ingress-nginx versions (v1.14.x), there's a separate `allow-snippet-annotations` flag but also the admission webhook has its own risky annotation check. \n\nOne option is to use the `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/server-snippet` annotation instead, but that applies to all paths in the server block... not what we want.\nAnother approach is to leverage the built-in `limit-rps` annotation for rate limiting, which doesn't require configuration snippets at all. Since this applies per nginx instance, with 3 replicas distributing traffic round-robin, I'd need to account for that—setting each replica to roughly 0.33 r/s would give me the ~1 r/s global limit I'm aiming for.\n\nBut there's a constraint: the annotation only accepts integer values with a minimum of 1 r/s per replica, which would result in 3 r/s effective globally. I could switch to `limit-rpm` instead for finer granularity—setting it to 20 requests per minute per replica would give me 60 rpm total, which equals 1 r/s. Though looking at my test scenario, it's firing 10 requests with 0.5 second intervals between them, which is actually 2 r/s, so I need to reconsider what rate limit actually makes sense here. 2 r/s total, which means each replica gets roughly 0.67 r/s. If I set the per-replica limit to 1 r/s, all requests would pass, but the test expects some to be rejected. I need to figure out what limit per replica would actually produce the ~1 r/s effective global rate the test is checking for.\n\nLet me reconsider using the native `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rpm` annotation instead, which handles the rate limiting internally without needing the webhook to process the ConfigMap snippet. The burst multiplier defaults to 5, which would allow 100 requests through initially—too permissive for this test. Setting `limit-burst-multiplier=1` would cap the burst at 20, so with 10 test requests distributed across 3 replicas, each replica receives only 3-4 requests, staying within the limit.\n\nBut this creates a different problem: the burst window absorbs the entire test batch, so all requests pass when some should be rejected. I need to think about how the requests actually distribute across replicas with round-robin load balancing and whether the timing of the requests relative to the rate limit window affects which ones get throttled. Setting ingress annotations...\n\nThe burst multiplier defaults to 5, which would allow the first 100 requests through before rate limiting kicks in—too lenient for a 10-request test. I could set `limit-rpm=20` with `limit-burst-multiplier=1` to tighten the burst, or go much lower with `limit-rpm=3` to ensure rejection, but I need to balance this with the requirement of achieving approximately 1 r/s effective throughput.\n\nRe-reading the task, the goal is clear: /api should be limited to ~1 request per second with 429 responses for excess traffic. The test sends 10 requests over ~5 seconds (2 r/s), so I should see rejections. The real problem is that nginx rate limiting doesn't share state across replicas—each one maintains its own counter independently. With round-robin distribution, the test client might hit different replicas each time, so each replica only sees ~0.67 r/s and allows everything through. I need a configuration that accounts for this replica isolation. more carefully. With `limit-rps=1`, the zone allows 1 token per second with a default burst multiplier of 5, giving a burst capacity of 6 total requests. Across 3 replicas, the 10 test requests distribute roughly evenly (3-4 per replica), so each replica can handle its share within the burst window before rate limiting kicks in.\n\nThe core issue is that small test loads spread across multiple replicas don't generate 429s because each replica's burst capacity absorbs the traffic. To trigger rate limit errors, I need to either reduce the burst multiplier significantly (like setting it to 1) or increase the request rate so that even the burst capacity gets exhausted quickly. Let me reconsider with `limit-rps=1` and `limit-burst-multiplier=1`, which gives only 1 token of burst capacity—this should force 429s when requests arrive faster than the 1 r/s rate allows. The key insight is that requests might not be evenly distributed across replicas—either because the client reuses connections (hitting the same replica repeatedly) or because of how Kubernetes load balancing works. Since curl typically closes connections between requests unless keepalive is enabled, each request should get load-balanced, but I need to reconsider whether the test setup actually achieves perfect round-robin distribution or if there's something about the connection handling that causes requests to cluster on a single replica.\n\nLooking at the actual solution path, it seems the challenge expects either using configuration snippets or the native rate-limiting annotations. The webhook is rejecting the snippet approach because `allow-snippet-annotations: \"true\"` in the ConfigMap isn't sufficient—in ingress-nginx v1.14.1 and later, the admission webhook requires the `--allow-snippet-annotations=true` startup flag on the controller itself, not just the ConfigMap setting, due to stricter security defaults introduced in v1.9+.\n\nI should verify what's actually deployed in the cluster versus what's in the configuration files to see if there's a mismatch between the ConfigMap setting and the controller's startup arguments.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1070,"cache_read_input_tokens":38192,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1070},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17a1dcd0-36fc-4f74-b9af-7bcabd04af45","uuid":"28f76103-1b72-47a6-accb-3903c96aed9b","request_id":"req_011Cc13sK8FWKXG4RM7gW3Eb"}
