{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UEsB88JED5yCBbiPBwZx7n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `limit_req_zone` is defined in the http block via the `http-snippet` ConfigMap setting (good). The `limit_req_status 429` is also set. But the `limit_req` directive is NOT in the location block for /api - that's what the `configuration-snippet` annotation should add.\n\nSince the controller is logging the error and not applying the annotation, I need a different approach. The `--enable-annotation-validation=false` flag does NOT disable the check in `store.go:951`.\n\nLet me think about alternatives:\n\n1. The annotation validation is in `store.go:951`. I need to find a way to make the controller apply the annotation despite the risk check.\n2. I could try using `server-snippet` instead of `configuration-snippet` to see if it has a lower risk level, or look for native annotations that don't trigger the risky validation checks.\n\nActually, the native annotations like `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps` are marked as lower risk and should be allowed. The real problem was that with three replicas using round-robin load balancing, each replica only sees about a third of the traffic, which made the burst size ineffective.\n\nLet me reconsider the `limit-rps` approach with a custom burst multiplier. If I set `limit-rps=1` with `limit-burst-multiplier=1`, that gives a burst of just 1 request. With requests spaced 1.5 seconds apart across three replicas, each replica would process roughly one request per 1.5 seconds, which should stay within the 1 request per second rate limit.\n\nNow I'm testing `limit-rpm=20` (0.33 r/s per replica) with a burst of 20 to see if that's more restrictive. With 10 requests arriving at 0.5-second intervals across 3 replicas, each replica receives about 4 requests over the 5-second window. The token bucket calculations show that even with the burst allowance, the excess tokens stay well below the burst limit, so all requests should pass.\n\nI'm reconsidering the approach entirely—instead of trying to work around the risk validation that's blocking the annotation at `store.go:951`, maybe I should try using a `server-snippet` annotation instead, which might have different security restrictions and allow me to inject the `limit_req` directive directly into the server block. So the `http-snippet` sets up the rate-limiting zone, but I need the actual `limit_req` directive in the location block for `/api`. The challenge is that `server-snippet` would apply to all locations on that server, including `/health`, which I don't want to rate-limit. I could try using `server-snippet` on one ingress and `configuration-snippet` on another to selectively apply rate-limiting, but that gets complicated with how the directives interact across multiple ingress resources.\n\nI'm realizing the core issue is that ingress-nginx's annotation system doesn't easily support per-location rate-limiting across separate ingress objects. I could patch the controller's validation logic to allow a custom annotation, but that means rebuilding the controller image. Alternatively, I could customize the nginx.conf template itself through a ConfigMap mount, which would let me add the `limit_req` directive directly for specific locations without relying on annotations.\n\nThe real constraint here is the test setup—10 requests at 0.5-second intervals across multiple replicas—and I need to figure out whether the native `limit-rps` annotation can actually handle that scenario. All requests pass because the inter-arrival time between requests at each replica exceeds the rate limit window, allowing the excess to fully drain. The key insight is that 429s only occur when requests arrive at a single replica faster than the rate allows. I'm working through the token bucket calculations with a rate of 0.3 r/s and burst multiplier of 1, which gives a burst capacity of 18. Checking each request at 1.5s intervals: the first request at t=0 passes with excess=1, then at t=1.5 the excess decreases to 0.55 before adding the next request, and by t=3 it's accumulated to 2.1—all well under the burst limit, so they continue passing.\n\nThe real constraint is that with 3 replicas and 10 requests spaced 0.5s apart, the burst capacity is too large to trigger any 429 responses, regardless of what native limit settings I configure.\n\nLet me reconsider `limit-connections` instead—it caps concurrent connections per IP, but since my sequential test only maintains one connection at a time, setting it to 1 wouldn't help either.\n\nActually, I think the core issue is different. The `configuration-snippet` annotation is stored in Kubernetes, but the controller is refusing to use it when generating the nginx config, even though I've already tried enabling snippet annotations in the ConfigMap, disabling annotation validation in the controller args, and removing the admission webhook. I need to dig into why the controller is still blocking it.\n\nMaybe I should look at patching the nginx.conf directly in the pods, though that won't persist across controller reloads. Or I could investigate what the `--enable-annotation-validation` flag actually controls—whether it's just about validation or if it affects how the controller processes annotations.\n\nLooking at the ingress-nginx source, the risk check in `store.go` seems separate from the annotation validation feature. The `allow-snippet-annotations` ConfigMap setting only controls whether snippets are included in the generated config, not whether the ingress gets blocked entirely. I need to check the v1.9 changelog to see what actually disables the risk check.\n\nThe release notes mention an `--annotations-risk-level` flag that was added to control which annotations are allowed, with \"Critical\" being the setting needed for snippets. But when I checked the help output for v1.14.1, this flag doesn't appear to exist anymore—it might have been renamed or removed in later versions.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":441,"cache_read_input_tokens":70336,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":441},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17a1dcd0-36fc-4f74-b9af-7bcabd04af45","uuid":"9f7147cf-fdf9-4f69-b648-1d3e1d648c60","request_id":"req_011Cc14d9kfq8wdRTGHn3dZa"}
